Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e01b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e02a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e02a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e02a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e02a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e02a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e02a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 001, task s01e02b.

  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 001, task s01e03b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e03b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e04b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e04b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e04b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e04b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e04b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e04b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 001, task s01e05a.

  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.

  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

The qform has been copied from sform. The difference in angle is 2e-06 radians. The difference in translation is 7.1e-15mm.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e05b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e05b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e05b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e05b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e05b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-001_task-s01e05b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e06a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e06a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e06a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e06a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e06a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e06a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 002, task s01e06b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

The qform has been copied from sform. The difference in angle is -9.6e-06 radians. The difference in translation is 1e-14mm.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 002, task s01e07b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e07b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 002, task s01e08a.

  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e08b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e08b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e08b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e08b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e08b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e08b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 002, task s01e09a.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e09a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e09a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e09a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e09a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-002_task-s01e09b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e10a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e10a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e10a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e10a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e10a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e10a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 003, task s01e10b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 003, task s01e11b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e11b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 003, task s01e12a.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e12b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e12b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e12b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e12b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e12b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e12b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 003, task s01e13a.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e13b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e13b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e13b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e13b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e13b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e13b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 003, task s01e14a.

Note on orientation: qform matrix overwritten

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e14a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e14a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e14a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e14a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e14a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-003_task-s01e14a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 004, task s01e15b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e15b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e16b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 004, task s01e17a.

  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s

  • Single-echo EPI sequence.

  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e17b_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e17b_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e17b_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e17b_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e17b_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e17b_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 004, task s01e18a.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e18a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e18a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-004_task-s01e18a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Susceptibility distortion correction

Results of performing susceptibility distortion correction (SDC) on the EPI

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-005_task-s01e19a_desc-sdc_bold.svg

Alignment of functional and anatomical MRI data (surface driven)

bbregister was used to generate transformations from EPI-space to T1w-space. Note that Nearest Neighbor interpolation is used in the reportlets in order to highlight potential spin-history and other artifacts, whereas final images are resampled using Lanczos interpolation.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-005_task-s01e19a_desc-bbregister_bold.svg

Brain mask and (anatomical/temporal) CompCor ROIs

Brain mask calculated on the BOLD signal (red contour), along with the regions of interest (ROIs) used in a/tCompCor for extracting physiological and movement confounding components.
The anatomical CompCor ROI (magenta contour) is a mask combining CSF and WM (white-matter), where voxels containing a minimal partial volume of GM have been removed.
The temporal CompCor ROI (blue contour) contains the top 2% most variable voxels within the brain mask.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-005_task-s01e19a_desc-rois_bold.svg

Variance explained by t/aCompCor components

The cumulative variance explained by the first k components of the t/aCompCor decomposition, plotted for all values of k. The number of components that must be included in the model in order to explain some fraction of variance in the decomposition mask can be used as a feature selection criterion for confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-005_task-s01e19a_desc-compcorvar_bold.svg

BOLD Summary

Summary statistics are plotted, which may reveal trends or artifacts in the BOLD data. Global signals calculated within the whole-brain (GS), within the white-matter (WM) and within cerebro-spinal fluid (CSF) show the mean BOLD signal in their corresponding masks. DVARS and FD show the standardized DVARS and framewise-displacement measures for each time point.
A carpet plot shows the time series for all voxels within the brain mask, or if --cifti-output was enabled, all grayordinates. Voxels are grouped into cortical (dark/light blue), and subcortical (orange) gray matter, cerebellum (green) and white matter and CSF (red), indicated by the color map on the left-hand side.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-005_task-s01e19a_desc-carpetplot_bold.svg

Correlations among nuisance regressors

Left: Heatmap summarizing the correlation structure among confound variables. (Cosine bases and PCA-derived CompCor components are inherently orthogonal.) Right: magnitude of the correlation between each confound time series and the mean global signal. Strong correlations might be indicative of partial volume effects and can inform decisions about feature orthogonalization prior to confound regression.

Get figure file: sub-06/figures/sub-06_ses-005_task-s01e19a_desc-confoundcorr_bold.svg

Reports for: session 005, task s01e19b.

Summary
  • Repetition time (TR): 1.49s
  • Phase-encoding (PE) direction: Anterior-Posterior
  • Single-echo EPI sequence.
  • Slice timing correction: Applied
  • Susceptibility distortion correction: PEB/PEPOLAR (phase-encoding based / PE-POLARity)
  • Registration: FreeSurfer bbregister (boundary-based registration, BBR) - 6 dof
  • Non-steady-state volumes: 0
